"Gleeson T., Smith L., Moosdorf N., Hartmann J., Dürr H.H., Manning A.H., Van Beek L.P.H., Jellinek A.M.","Mapping permeability over the surface of the Earth",2011,"Geophysical Research Letters","38","2", L02401,"","",,,10.1029/2010GL045565,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-79251539622&partnerID=40&md5=ccea7c8bc3abc63ed77bb4dabaf51ebd","Department of Earth and Ocean Sciences, University of British Columbia, 6339 Stores Rd., Vancouver, BC V6T 1Z4, Canada; Institute for Biogeochemistry and Marine Chemistry, Klim Campus, University of Hamburg, Bundesstraße 55, D-20146 Hamburg, Germany; Department of Physical Geography, Faculty of Geosciences, Utrecht University, PO Box 80115, NL-3508 TC Utrecht, Netherlands; U.S. Geological Survey, Mail Stop 973, PO Box 25046, Denver, CO 80225-0046, United States","Gleeson, T., Department of Earth and Ocean Sciences, University of British Columbia, 6339 Stores Rd., Vancouver, BC V6T 1Z4, Canada; Smith, L., Department of Earth and Ocean Sciences, University of British Columbia, 6339 Stores Rd., Vancouver, BC V6T 1Z4, Canada; Moosdorf, N., Institute for Biogeochemistry and Marine Chemistry, Klim Campus, University of Hamburg, Bundesstraße 55, D-20146 Hamburg, Germany; Hartmann, J., Institute for Biogeochemistry and Marine Chemistry, Klim Campus, University of Hamburg, Bundesstraße 55, D-20146 Hamburg, Germany; Dürr, H.H., Department of Physical Geography, Faculty of Geosciences, Utrecht University, PO Box 80115, NL-3508 TC Utrecht, Netherlands; Manning, A.H., U.S. Geological Survey, Mail Stop 973, PO Box 25046, Denver, CO 80225-0046, United States; Van Beek, L.P.H., Department of Physical Geography, Faculty of Geosciences, Utrecht University, PO Box 80115, NL-3508 TC Utrecht, Netherlands; Jellinek, A.M., Department of Earth and Ocean Sciences, University of British Columbia, 6339 Stores Rd., Vancouver, BC V6T 1Z4, Canada","Permeability, the ease of fluid flow through porous rocks and soils, is a fundamental but often poorly quantified component in the analysis of regional-scale water fluxes. Permeability is difficult to quantify because it varies over more than 13 orders of magnitude and is heterogeneous and dependent on flow direction. Indeed, at the regional scale, maps of permeability only exist for soil to depths of 1-2 m. Here we use an extensive compilation of results from hydrogeologic models to show that regional-scale (>5 km) permeability of consolidated and unconsolidated geologic units below soil horizons (hydrolithologies) can be characterized in a statistically meaningful way. The representative permeabilities of these hydrolithologies are used to map the distribution of near-surface (on the order of 100 m depth) permeability globally and over North America. The distribution of each hydrolithology is generally scale independent. The near-surface mean permeability is of the order of ∼5 × 10-14 m2. The results provide the first global picture of near-surface permeability and will be of particular value for evaluating global water resources and modeling the influence of climate-surface-subsurface interactions on global climate change. Copyright © 2011 by the American Geophysical Union.",,"Flow of fluids; Geologic models; Hydrogeology; Soils; Water resources; Fluid flow; Geologic units; Global climate changes; Global water resources; Hydrolithology; Near-surface; On flow; Orders of magnitude; Porous rocks; Regional scale; Soil horizon; Water flux; Climate change; climate change; fluid flow; global climate; permeability; soil depth; soil horizon; water flow; North America",,,,,,"Anyah, R.O., Weaver, C.P., Miguez-Macho, G., Fan, Y., Robock, A., Incorporating water table dynamics in climate modeling: 3. Simulated groundwater influence on coupled land-atmosphere variability (2008) J. Geophys. Res., 113, pp. D07103. , doi:10.1029/2007JD009087; (2008) Groundwater Resources of the World Scale 1: 25 000 000, WHYMAP, , BGR and UNESCO Hanover, Germany; Brace, W.F., Permeability of 